(ScrollX, ScrollY, BackgroundImage); // Draw scrolling stars StarY := ScrollY; while StarY < ClientHeight do begin StarX := ScrollX; while StarX < ClientWidth do begin Canvas.Draw(StarX, StarY, StarImage); Inc(StarX, StarImage.Width + 50); // Adjust spacing between stars end; Inc(StarY, StarImage.Height + 50); end; // Draw scrolling comets CometY := ScrollY; while CometY < ClientHeight do begin CometX := ScrollX; while CometX < ClientWidth do begin Canvas.Draw(CometX, CometY, CometImage); Inc(CometX, CometImage.Width + 200); // Adjust spacing between comets end; Inc(CometY, CometImage.Height + 200); end; end; \`\`\` In this code, we use the \`ScrollX\` and \`ScrollY\` variables to control the scrolling speed of the background based on the player's position. We then draw the background image using the \`Canvas.Draw\` method. Next, we draw the scrolling stars by using nested \`while\` loops to iterate through the visible area of the form. Each iteration, we draw a star at the corresponding \`StarX\` and \`StarY\` position, and then increment \`StarX\` to space out the stars horizontally and \`StarY\` to move to the next row. Similarly, we draw the scrolling comets by using nested \`while\` loops. Each iteration, we draw a comet at the corresponding \`CometX\` and \`CometY\` position, and then increment \`CometX\` to space out the comets horizontally and \`CometY\` to move to the next row. Adjust the values of \`StarImage.Width\`, \`StarImage.Height\`, \`CometImage.Width\`, and \`CometImage.Height\` as well as the spacing values (\`50\` and \`200\` in the example) to achieve the desired visual effect. Remember to include the actual file names of your background, star, and comet images in the \`LoadFromFile\` calls when initializing the resources. I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions."},{"instruction":"tu es expert en création de contenu marketing depuis 20 ans et je veux que tu me rédiges une série d'email marketing pour annoncer mon événeme